Let G be a (connected) Lie group, and \Gamma an abstract group. Denote by \mathrm{Hom}(\Gamma,G) the set of homomorphisms of the group \Gamma to the group G with the pointwise convergence topology, that is, a sequence \rho\_{n}\in\mathrm{Hom}(\Gamma,G) is said to algebraically converge to a homomorphism \rho if \lim\_{n\to\infty}\rho\_{n}(\gamma)=\rho(\gamma) for every \gamma\in\Gamma.

Let \Gamma\_{n} be a sequence of discrete subgroups of \mathrm{Isom}(\mathbb{H}^{d}). We say that \Gamma\_{n} *converge in the Chabauty topology* to \Gamma if the groups converge in the Chabauty topology on closed subsets of G. Convergence in this topology can be characterized as follows:

* •

  every \gamma\in\Gamma is the limit of some sequence \{\gamma\_{n}\} with \gamma\_{n}\in\Gamma\_{n};
* •

  if \gamma\_{n}\to\gamma is a convergent sequence with \gamma\_{n}\in\Gamma\_{n}, then \gamma\in\Gamma.

Let \mathscr{H}\_{d} denote the set of complete hyperbolic manifolds \mathbb{H}^{d}/\Gamma, with \Gamma<\mathrm{Isom}(\mathbb{H}^{d}) a discrete subgroup, and \mathscr{F}\_{d}\subset\mathscr{H}\_{d} the subset of finite-volume manifolds (i.e. with \Gamma being a lattice). We equip \mathscr{H}\_{d} with the topology of geometric convergence defined as the Chabauty topology on \mathrm{Isom}(\mathbb{H}^{d}). That is, hyperbolic manifolds M\_{n}=\mathbb{H}^{d}/\Gamma\_{n} converge to M=\mathbb{H}^{d}/\Gamma geometrically if \Gamma\_{n}\to\Gamma in the Chabauty topology.

We will need another notion of convergence which happens to be equivalent to the geometric one in the setting of hyperbolic manifolds. For a manifold X, let \mathcal{OF}(X) denote the orthogonal frame bundle of X. Let (M\_{1},v\_{1}) and (M\_{2},v\_{2}) be complete hyperbolic d–manifolds with orthonormal baseframes v\_{1}\in\mathcal{OF}(M\_{1}), v\_{2}\in\mathcal{OF}(M\_{2}) based at points x\_{1}\in M\_{1}, x\_{2}\in M\_{2}.
We say that a map f:(X\_{1},v\_{1})\to(X\_{2},v\_{2}) is a *framed (K,r)–approximate isometry* between (M\_{1},v\_{1}) and (M\_{2},v\_{2}) if:

* •

  f:X\_{1}\to X\_{2} is a diffeomorphism of domains X\_{j}\subset M\_{j};
* •

  B\_{M\_{1}}(x\_{1},r)\subset(X\_{1},x\_{1})\subset(M\_{1},x\_{1}) and
  B\_{M\_{2}}(x\_{2},r)\subset(X\_{2},x\_{2})\subset(M\_{2},x\_{2});
* •

  Df(v\_{1})=v\_{2} (the baseframe is preserved);
* •

