Suppose now that M\_{i}=\mathbb{H}^{d}/\Gamma\_{i} is a sequence of hyperbolic manifolds with baseframes v\_{i}\in\mathcal{OF}(M\_{i}) based at points x\_{i}\in M\_{i}, and let M=\mathbb{H}^{d}/\Gamma be a hyperbolic manifold with baseframe v\in\mathcal{OF}(M) based at x\in M. The sequence (M\_{i},v\_{i}) converges to (M,v) in the induced refined Gromov–Hausdorff topology if if there exist (K\_{i},r\_{i})–approximate isometries f\_{i}:(M\_{i},v\_{i})\to(M,v) with K\_{i}\to 1 and r\_{i}\to\infty as i\to\infty.

The following theorem (see Benedetti–Petronio [4, Theorem E.1.13 and Remark E.1.19] and Canary–Epstein–Green [8, Theorem 3.2.9 and Corollary 3.2.11]) shows that the geometric convergence is equivalent to the classical pointed Gromov–Hausdorff convergence and the stronger convergence in the refined Gromov–Hausdorff topology, as well as to the pointed Gromov–Hausdorff convergence of the corresponding Dirichlet fundamental polyhedra.

###### Theorem 2.8.

Let d\geq 2. The following are equivalent.

1. (1)

   A sequence of torsion-free discrete subgroups \Gamma\_{n}<\mathrm{Isom}(\mathbb{H}^{d}) geometrically converges to a torsion-free discrete subgroup \Gamma<\mathrm{Isom}(\mathbb{H}^{d}).
2. (2)

   The pointed hyperbolic manifolds (\mathbb{H}^{d}/\Gamma\_{n},v\_{n}) converge to (\mathbb{H}^{d}/\Gamma,v) in the refined Gromov–Hausdorff topology for some choice of orthonormal baseframes v\_{n}\in\mathcal{OF}(\mathbb{H}^{d}/\Gamma\_{n}) and v\in\mathcal{OF}(\mathbb{H}^{d}/\Gamma).
3. (3)

   For a fixed origin o\in\mathbb{H}^{d}, the Dirichlet fundamental polyhedra D\_{\Gamma\_{n}}(o) converge in the pointed Gromov–Hausdorff topology to the Dirichlet fundamental polyhedron D\_{\Gamma}(o). The corresponding side-pairing generators of \Gamma\_{n} also converge to that of \Gamma.

###### Corollary 2.8.1.

If \Gamma\_{n}\to\Gamma geometrically, then for any compact subset K\subset M=\mathbb{H}^{d}/\Gamma there is N>0 such that for any n>N there exists a (1+\varepsilon\_{n})-bi-Lipschitz embedding \phi\_{n}:K\hookrightarrow M\_{n}=\mathbb{H}^{d}/\Gamma\_{n}, which is a diffeomorphism onto its image \phi\_{n}(K).

